<section label="higher-order-lhcc">
	<title> Higher-Order LHCC Equations </title>
	
	<introduction>
		<p> 
			We’ve seen how to solve second-order LHCC equations by finding the roots of the characteristic equation. The same idea extends to <term>higher-order</term> LHCC equations—those involving third derivatives, fourth derivatives, or beyond. While the general structure stays the same, higher-order equations require us to handle more roots and build longer general solutions.
		</p>
	</introduction>

	<paragraphs>
		<title> The Characteristic Equation </title>

		<p>
		The standard <m>n</m>th-order LHCC equation has the form:
		</p>

		<me>
		a_n y^{(n)} + a_{n-1} y^{(n-1)} + \cdots + a_1 y' + a_0 y = 0
		</me>

		<p>
		To find solutions, we assume <m>y = e^{rx}</m>. Substituting this into the equation yields:
		</p>

		<md>
		<mrow> a_n r^n e^{rx} + a_{n-1} r^{n-1} e^{rx} + \cdots + a_1 r e^{rx} + a_0 e^{rx} \amp = 0 </mrow>
		<mrow> (a_n r^n + a_{n-1} r^{n-1} + \cdots + a_1 r + a_0) e^{rx} \amp = 0 </mrow>
		</md>

		<p>
		Since <m>e^{rx} \ne 0</m>, we obtain the <term>characteristic equation</term>:
		</p>

		<me>
		a_n r^n + a_{n-1} r^{n-1} + \cdots + a_1 r + a_0 = 0
		</me>

		<p>
		This is a polynomial of degree <m>n</m>, and solving it gives us the roots that define the structure of the general solution.
		</p>

	</paragraphs> 

	<paragraphs>
		<title> Building the General Solution </title>

		<p>
  The form of the general solution depends entirely on the roots of the characteristic equation. Each root contributes one or more terms to the solution, depending on whether it is:
</p>

<ul>
  <li> Real and distinct </li>
  <li> Repeated (with multiplicity greater than one) </li>
  <li> Complex (appears in a conjugate pair) </li>
</ul>

<p>
  We’ll review each case and how it contributes to the general solution.
</p>

	</paragraphs> <paragraphs> <title> Real and Distinct Roots </title>

		<p>
  If all <m>n</m> roots <m>r_1, r_2, \dots, r_n</m> are real and distinct, then the general solution is:
</p>

<me>
  y = c_1 e^{r_1 x} + c_2 e^{r_2 x} + \cdots + c_n e^{r_n x}
</me>

<p>
  Each term corresponds to one root, and the constants <m>c_1, \dots, c_n</m> account for initial conditions.
</p>

</paragraphs> <paragraphs> <title> Repeated Roots </title>

	<p>
  If a root <m>r</m> appears with multiplicity <m>k</m>, it contributes <m>k</m> terms to the solution. These terms are:
</p>

<me>
  e^{r x}, \quad x e^{r x}, \quad x^2 e^{r x}, \quad \dots, \quad x^{k-1} e^{r x}
</me>

<p>
  So, for example, if <m>r = 3</m> is a triple root, the corresponding part of the solution is:
</p>

<me>
  y = c_1 e^{3x} + c_2 x e^{3x} + c_3 x^2 e^{3x}
</me>

</paragraphs> <paragraphs> <title> Complex Roots </title>

	<p>
  If the characteristic equation has complex roots, they must occur in conjugate pairs. For instance, if <m>r = \alpha + i\beta</m> and <m>\alpha - i\beta</m> are roots, then they contribute the following two terms:
</p>

<me>
  y = e^{\alpha x} (c_1 \cos(\beta x) + c_2 \sin(\beta x))
</me>

<p>
  This form ensures the general solution remains real-valued, even though the roots are complex.
</p>

</paragraphs> <paragraphs> <title> Putting It All Together </title>

	<p>
  For a general <m>n</m>th-order LHCC equation, the full general solution includes one term for each root of the characteristic polynomial, following the guidelines above:
</p>

<ul>
  <li> One exponential for each real, distinct root. </li>
  <li> <m>k</m> terms of the form <m>x^m e^{rx}</m> if <m>r</m> has multiplicity <m>k</m>. </li>
  <li> Two terms of the form <m>e^{\alpha x} \cos(\beta x)</m> and <m>e^{\alpha x} \sin(\beta x)</m> for each complex conjugate pair. </li>
</ul>

<p>
  Let’s practice by constructing general solutions given the roots of the characteristic equation.
</p>

</paragraphs>

<example xml:id="roots-to-general-solution">
	<title> Constructing the General Solution from Roots </title>
	<statement> <p> For each set of characteristic roots, write the general solution of the LHCC equation.

	</p> 
	
	<ol>
		<li><m>r = 2,\quad -3,\quad 0</m></li>
		<li><m>r = 4 + i,\quad 4 - i,\quad -1</m></li>
		<li><m>r = -2\ (\text{triple root}),\quad 5</m></li>
		<li><m>r = i,\quad -i,\quad 3,\quad 3\ (\text{double root})</m></li>
	</ol>
</statement>
	<solution>
		<ol>
			<li><me>y = c_1 e^{2x} + c_2 e^{-3x} + c_3</me></li>
		<li><me>y = e^{4x} (c_1 \cos x + c_2 \sin x) + c_3 e^{-x}</me></li>
		<li><me>y = c_1 e^{-2x} + c_2 x e^{-2x} + c_3 x^2 e^{-2x} + c_4 e^{5x}</me></li>
		<li><me>y = c_1 \cos x + c_2 \sin x + c_3 e^{3x} + c_4 x e^{3x} + c_5 x^2 e^{3x}</me></li>
	</ol>
</solution>
</example>
<objectives>
			<ul>
			<li>
				Higher-order LHCC equations are solved by finding the roots of the characteristic polynomial.
			</li>
			<li>
				Each root contributes one or more terms to the general solution, depending on whether it is real, repeated, or complex.
			</li>
			<li>
				The full general solution contains <m>n</m> linearly independent terms, one for each order of the differential equation.
			</li>
		</ul>
	</objectives>

